[Although the report attributes the exposure to crabs when machine translated, the picture in the original report appears to be a crayfish. The Spanish word for crab is cangrejo and for crayfish is cangrejo de rio.

The manifestations of human tularemia vary depending on the site of inoculation, ulceroglandular refers to a local ulcerative lesion associated with regional lymphadenitis. Other forms include oroglandular, oculoglandular, pneumonia and the typhoidal form in which there is bacteremia without focal involvement. The diagnosis can be made by culture or by demonstrating a serological rise.

This report from 2001 illustrates a previous crayfish-related tularemia outbreak in Spain:
Anda P, Segura del Pozo J, Diaz Garcia JM, et al. Waterborne outbreak of tularemia associated with crayfish fishing. Emerg Infect Dis. 2001; 7(3 Suppl): 575-82. https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/7/7/01-7740_article
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Abstract
--------
"In 1997, an outbreak of human tularemia associated with hare-hunting in central Spain affected 585 patients. We describe the identification of _Francisella tularensis_ biovar palaearctica in a 2nd outbreak of ulceroglandular tularemia associated with crayfish (_Procambarus clarkii_) fishing in a contaminated freshwater stream distant from the hare-associated outbreak. The 2nd outbreak occurred 1 year after the 1st."

Crayfish, also known as crawfish, crawdads, freshwater lobsters, or mudbugs, "are freshwater crustaceans resembling small lobsters (to which they are related).... Taxonomically, they are members of the superfamilies Astacoidea and Parastacoidea. They breathe through feather-like gills [and are found in bodies of water that do not freeze to the bottom]. Some species are found in brooks and streams, where fresh water is running, while others thrive in swamps, ditches, and paddy fields.... Crayfish feed on [living and dead] animals and plants" (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crayfish).

Aragon is in north eastern Spain and can be seen on a map at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aragon. - Mod.LL

HealthMap/ProMED map of Zaragoza, Aragon, Spain: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8593242,18349.]
